# Component conventions

Every component in `src/renderer/components/` follows this pattern. See `design/components.md` for the inventory and per-component contracts.

## File structure

```
src/renderer/components/
  <Domain>/<Component>.tsx   ← grouped by screen/feature (Today, Capture, Window)
  primitives/<Primitive>.tsx ← shared design-system primitives (Button, Chip, Icon, …)
  Icons.tsx                  ← icon set
```

Primitives go in `components/primitives/`. Screen-specific components live under their feature folder.

## Props API

- Define props as `type Props = { … }` above the component. No `React.FC`. No inline prop types.
- Required props first, optional last. Defaults via destructuring (`{ size = 'md', … }`).
- Variant unions are explicit: `variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'ghost'`. No boolean flags that mean different things together.
- Children only when the component genuinely renders nested content. Otherwise use named props (`label`, `icon`, `meta`).

## States to consider for every interactive component

1. Default
2. Hover
3. Focus (visible focus ring — Apple HIG)
4. Active / pressed
5. Disabled
6. Loading (if it triggers async work)

A component that doesn't have a real visual for one of these states must still handle it correctly (e.g. disabled buttons block clicks).

## Anti-patterns (fix on sight)

| Bad | Why | Fix |
|-----|-----|-----|
| Inline `style={{ }}` with raw values | Bypasses tokens | Move to CSS class + semantic token |
| `<button>` styled inline per use | Should be a primitive | Extract `<Button variant="…" />` |
| Boolean flags `isPrimary` AND `isDanger` | Variant unions are clearer | `variant?: 'primary' \| 'danger'` |
| Passing className from outside to override style | Breaks encapsulation | Add a proper `variant` or `tone` prop |
| Component knows about its screen's layout | Cross-cutting concern | Layout is the parent's job; component is unaware |

## Accessibility floor

- Every interactive element needs an `aria-label` if not labelled visibly.
- Buttons that toggle state announce both states (`Mark complete` / `Mark incomplete`, like the existing `TaskRow`).
- Focus visible on every focusable element. Never `outline: none` without a replacement focus indicator.

## When extracting a new primitive

Invoke `needle-build-component`. It enforces the full pattern: props type → variants → states → tokens → story (when Ladle exists).
